  \begin{abstract}
  We derive General Relativity as an emergent, effective description of the fundamental biquaternionic field $\Theta(q,\tau)$ rather than as a fundamental theory. The metric tensor $g_{\mu\nu}$ is constructed as a bilinear functional of $\Theta$ and its covariant derivatives. From this emergent metric, we compute Christoffel symbols and curvature tensors using standard differential geometry. We then derive the Einstein field equation $G_{\mu\nu} = \kappa T^{(\Theta)}_{\mu\nu}$ where the stress-energy tensor has a clear origin in $\Theta$-field dynamics. We prove that classical GR emerges in the limit of slowly varying phase and suppressed diffusion, while preserving diffeomorphism invariance throughout.
  \end{abstract}
